As you travel along this path there will be good days as well as bad days. The ability to overcoming those bad ones depend on your internal strength. To all of the family members, Your Soldier will depend on you to be there for them when they need it most.  To the soldiers remember this, "You are NOT in The Army, YOU ARE THE ARMY" I wish you and your family all the best in this new journey. Stay ARMY STRONG!

comment: I was a paratrooper in the French foreign legion. 3rd cie, 2eme REP, Calvi. Had about 60 jumps in my first 4 years. I always would get in 1st position, right in the door because it‚Äôs the safest spot. You have no one on one side of you therefore less crowded and less dangerous. Less a chance of colliding with another parachute or one passing underneath you near the ground. That last one is the worse, they take the wind out of your chute and cause you to fall very fast with no resistance, smacking into the ground.

comment:
USMC Captain dropped to IRR 2015 after it became apparent the road we were heading down...a path that doesnt aim to protect the constitution or the Average American CITIZEN. The sad thing is that Russia and China are bad guys but we have completely destroyed our own moral authority to grandstand on the world stage.

I put in my conscientious objector status back in 2019 when they called me up for muster just a few days after they tried to get us to go to war with Iran, again... 

And now a quote from a man wiser than me.

War is a racket. It always has been.

I spent thirty- three years and four months in active military service as a member of this country‚Äôs most agile military force, the Marine Corps. I served in all commissioned ranks from Second Lieutenant to Major-General. And during that period, I spent most of my time being a high class muscle- man for Big Business, for Wall Street and for the Bankers. In short, I was a racketeer, a gangster for capitalism.

General Smedley Butler, USMC

comment: I can't believe that we let this happen! There is no turning back now. There is no honor or nothing sacred anymore.  I was stationed at FT BRAGG  and spent some of the best years of my life there with some of the bravest and badest soldiers in the Military.  We were constantly indoctrinated with tradition an honor and we fought to uphold these things. Some clowns ü§° at the DOD just came in totally un opposed and changed the names of these bases. Ft. Bragg was the name of the base we trained,  lived formed a brotherhood and friendships that last a lifetime.  The name Bragg is tied to all these memories it has nothing to do with the Confederate General from NC that lost more battles for the south that he actually helped the north. But the name Bragg you just cannot change and erase you might as well piss on all the Graves of the soldiers that left Ft Bragg to defend this country and never came home! If you did not live there or were not stationed there you know nothing of this. They started by changing the names of products like Aunt Jemima pancakes, syrup. Did that really make a fckn difference.  America as I know it is gone we have been destroyed not by a foreign enemy but by something far worse some Agenda that has warped the minds of are children and they have done away with any sense of rational logic . No one was honoring General Bragg but we reflected on a time when brothers fought brothers over some ideology and if we don't remember this dark time in are past we are doomed to repeat it and I'm afraid the actions of are government and leaders starting with giving in to this new agenda that is tearing are Country apart is leading us to another even darker chapter in our country's history üíî

comment: Everyone wonders why this is taught this way...this is technique is taught because not everyone can throw, just like everyone can't shoot a rifle or firearm. This is Basic Training, and is just a technique. Take it from a former Drill Sergeant that you want to have several practices (Drills) like this before getting to what we refer to as "Live Bay" where you throw live grenades. We begin teaching "proper grip" in the chow hall (DFAC) with trainees carrying their glass filled with water or juice to develop muscle memory in preparation to throwing live, so that it feels natural.

comment: I looked at the comments on a couple other spots and they look like these. There's no doubt leadership fu**** up on the changes in policy and tolerance for ideological BS.   This nation is going to be in serious trouble if they don't come straight out and admit to the world what they were trying to do and name the forces they were bowing to - and detail to the American public the standards of operation they're returning to.  And those standards need to be whatever was in place during the 3-5 years BEFORE their highest recruitment successes.  When they were weeding out people they didn't want. When they had so many and such good applicants they could be a selective service. And they need to get real.  Their "audience" - their "customer base" isn't people who were happy about the Target/Bud Light/ Trans-Navy crap.   People need to know that they're going to serve in the military their parents and grandparents served in and that they're job stress will be about doing the most important job in the US  - not worrying about hurting people's feelings who aren't mentally well enough to do the job if they themselves are that worried about their feelings. Harassment is one thing... real harassment.  But  the people in our military need to be the mentally and emotionally and socially toughest, best balanced, and most well people in our nation. Not the Tick-Tock dregs of society.

comment:
I was USMC 90-94, and when we did the gas chamber in Boot Camp the DI's made us answer questions, usually what one or more of our General Orders.  When I my annual gas chamber we usually sang the ENTIRE Marine Corps Hymn in the gas chamber.  Snot flowing from your nose, skin itching/burning, eyes watering/burning but still standing up proud singing like fools all the way through it.  Then marching out the door carrying our masks.  No one ever said we were the sharpest knives in the drawer.  The did say we were the ones you REALLY didn't want to mess with.
God Bless all the other Vets, and all these young boys and girls out there who put it on the line for our great nation.

Semper Fi.

author: Jim Allen
name: Army Mariners Demonstrate Benefits of Watercraft Presence
description:
When it comes to logistics and readiness, the Pacific region's essentially a gigantic waterworld that demands a team effort in maximizing even the most uncharacteristic capabilities of each service and organization. Two crews of Army mariners from the 97th Transportation Company out of Fort Eustis, Va., traveled across the Pacific seas for five continuous months in their Landing Craft Utility (LCU) vessels successfully demonstrating how operationalizing the unique Army capability in the region contributes to that team effort.

With 8th Theater Sustainment Command at the lead, and 10th Regional Support Group exercising operational command from its headquarters in Okinawa, the endeavor was labeled Pacific Utility and Logistics Support Enabler-Watercraft, or PULSE-W. While relatively simple in its concept -- maintain an enduring presence of Army watercraft that cost-effectively delivers cargo throughout the Pacific -- PULSE-W produced results reflecting immeasurable potential when it comes to supporting joint and multinational forces, and decreasing watercraft response times to natural disasters in the region.

comment: I am a Fort Gordon MP, Retired after 3 Combat Tours and 29 Operational Deployments. I am one of the MPs who transitioned the MP Corps from a Garrison Puke MOS to a Combat Arm. Those of us who went from Vietnam (me) to Somalia made the MP Corps a Strong Arm of the Combat Arms. Those soldiers who I lead in Germany and Ft Campbell then back in Germany where the Senior NCOs during Iraq and Afghanistan. They instilled that Combat Spirit into our Current MPs. Yes, the MP Corps is still the Draft Picks for LAPD, Dallas PD, Miami Dade PD etc, but they are so much more than COPS, they are WARRIORS

comment:
When I was a kid 20 some years ago, and the first COD came out, a big debate was whether or not these games were desensitizing us kids to violence. 

I think everyone arguing over this missed the point. Instead of arguing over desensitization, the focus should have been whether or not these games would serve as tools of propaganda. 

When the US Army uses directly COD references in their videos there is no debate; COD has the ability to serve as the some of the most effective propaganda in history, whether intended or not. 

Beware the koolaid.

comment: I recently attended my grandfather‚Äôs funeral. He fought in WW2. The men that showed up to send him off, in uniform, with the rifle salute, never knew him personally. They showed up nonetheless, in full regalia, with full honors as if they had served side by side. He was the last surviving member of his bomber group. I have never been so moved by an act of solidarity in my life.

comment: Happy Birthday Army.....Today is a GREAT Day for celebrations, for today we also celebrate Flag Day. Two unique events in our Nations History that are so intertwined. With all that our Nation is facing internally, it seems that the only thing for certain that we can depend on, is the loyalty and dedication of our Army. I know that there is a lot of discussion about the Army going back to the phrase "Be All You Can Be!" As a Soldier for Life, who served from 72-92, this phrase makes more sense today and is actually more than just a slogan. It is something to strive for, a goal for which we all should strive to be everyday.  To all the parents who have sons and daughters in the Army, thank you for all you do to support them. For all those who are looking for a role model, the American Soldier is that role model. They are the ones who wear the jersey of a real hero. They are the ones who place needs of others before their own. Go Army!!
